[4] EU Reference AI lab report on the developing situation with H5N8 HPAI
Date: Mon 24 Nov 2014 [accessed]
Source: Report, extraordinary EU PAFF Committee meeting, Brussels 20 Nov 2014 [summarised, edited]
http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/docs/20141120_ah_avian-influenza_eurl.pdf


[The following summary is included in the presentation delivered by Ian Brown, Director EURL (Avian Influenza EU Reference Laboratory) during the extraordinary meeting of PAFF Committee, section Animal Health and Welfare, convened in Brussels on 20 Nov 2014, addressing "the developing situation with H5N8 HPAI." - Mod.AS]

Summary
1. Following the recent incidents involving detection of H5N8 HPAI in poultry in Germany, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, the EURL have reviewed data available on the wild birds tested as part of the EU surveillance system from 2013, and preliminary data for 2014, in terms of spatial, temporal and species configuration. We have also included some ornithological data available in the public domain.

2. A passive surveillance system (testing birds found dead or ill) for avian influenza in wild birds is in place in EU Member States (MS) according to Commission Decision 2010/367/EU with the objective of timely detection of HPAI of subtype H5N1.

3. Infection with H5N8 HPAI lineage 2.3.4.6 has been found in many wild birds found dead in the Republic of Korea and also in apparently healthy wild mallards [ducks] in eastern China (_Anas platyrhynchos_) over the last 12 months.

4. Several of the species found infected with this lineage of H5N8 HPAI in East Asia also occur in Europe e.g. mallard, bean goose (_Anser fabalis_), white-fronted goose (_Anser albifrons_).

5. Wild waterbird flyways from the areas affected in Asia are predominantly north-south in orientation, and movement to EU MS of a significant number of these birds is highly unlikely. However, contiguous populations of some relevant species exist through this region, and movements of wild birds in west and central Asia to EU MS are more likely, e.g. Common Pochard (_Aythya ferina_) [duck].

6. If this virus were to be present in wild bird populations in the EU and cause significant morbidity or mortality, the wild bird passive surveillance activities of MS would have utility for the detection of this virus.

7. The sensitivity of the surveillance system in wild birds is likely to vary among MS and among regions within MS.

8. While the sensitivity of the surveillance is not equivalent to the number of wild birds tested over a period of time, this measure is likely to be an indicator of sensitivity when considering the relevance of the species involved.

9. Rapid evaluation indicates that the EU recommended diagnostic tests (Decision 2010/367/EU ) for the detection of influenza A viruses and specifically H5 by PCR as prescribed in the EU AI diagnostic manual (Decision 2006/437/EC) are fit for purpose and will reliably detect H5N8 HPAI.

--
